to the editor re disabled win halt to notations of special arrangements on tests front page feb 8 the agreement of the educational testing service to stop flagging the scores of people with disabilities who have received accommodations on several tests like the graduate record examination is indeed a victory for the disability community but it is disturbing that the testing service refuses to discontinue flagging sat scores test administrators flag tests because they believe that whenever someone receives more time he or she will score higher although this might seem intuitive repeated studies refute this test administrators must recognize that flagging exams is unnecessary unfairly stigmatizing and discriminatory ruth lowenkron new york feb 10 2001 the writer is an adjunct professor of disability law at cuny law school

